{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:48:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:48:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.07,0.04,0.16,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66569"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"7943"},{"type":"tags","id":"8105"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22274"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66569"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of erythematous patches on his trunk and arms. He migrated from Brazil two years ago. He reports that these patches feel numb and he has noticed weakness in his right hand when gripping objects. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He drinks 9 standard drinks only on weekends at parties for the last year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple well-defined erythematous patches with reduced sensation to light touch and pinprick. The right ulnar nerve is thickened and tender on palpation. There is weakness of the right first dorsal interosseous muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leprosy","Vitamin B12 deficiency","Sarcoidosis","Cutaneous tuberculosis","Multiple mononeuropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eleprosy\u003C/strong\u003E (Hansen\u0027s disease), a chronic infection by \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium leprae\u003C/em\u003E (\u003Cem\u003EM. leprae\u003C/em\u003E) and \u003Cem\u003EM. lepromatosis\u003C/em\u003E causing damage to the peripheral nerves. The key diagnostic features include erythematous patches with sensory loss, thickened peripheral nerves (particularly the ulnar nerve), and associated muscle weakness in the distribution of affected nerves. Patients may also present with hypopigmented patches, scaling, erythema nodosum leprosum or ulcers. The patient\u0027s origin from Brazil, an endemic region, adds further support to the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of leprosy can be confirmed through slit skin smear examination for acid-fast bacilli or skin biopsy from the active border of a lesion. Early diagnosis and treatment with multi-drug therapy is crucial to prevent permanent nerve damage and disability. Sadly though multidrug treatment is effective, the stigma of leprosy and the long-term neurological disabilities are ongoing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause neurological symptoms including peripheral neuropathy and weakness with heavy alcoholism, but does not cause the characteristic skin changes with sensory loss or thickened peripheral nerves seen in this case. It would also typically present with other features such as glossitis and macrocytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with skin lesions and peripheral neuropathy, but the skin lesions typically do not show sensory loss. Additionally, sarcoidosis commonly affects multiple organ systems and may present with respiratory symptoms, which are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with skin lesions but these are typically more nodular or ulcerative. While it can occur in patients from endemic regions, it does not typically cause peripheral nerve thickening or sensory loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple mononeuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the peripheral nerve involvement but would not account for the characteristic skin changes with sensory loss. This diagnosis is typically associated with systemic conditions such as vasculitis or diabetes, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardinal signs of leprosy include hypopigmented or reddish patches with loss of sensation, thickened peripheral nerves, and positive skin smear for acid-fast bacilli."],"references":["White C, Franco-Paredes C. Leprosy in the 21st Century. Clinical Microbiology Reviews. 2014. Available at: https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/cmr.00079-13","Chen KH, Lin CY, Su SB, Chen KT. Leprosy: A Review of Epidemiology, Clinical Diagnosis, and Management. Journal of Tropical Medicine. 2022. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9273393/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52022"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T00:44:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T00:45:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9413"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66569"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCoun